#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:3
msgid "Loading custom Python code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:5
msgid ""
"Pyodide provides a simple API {js:func}`pyodide.runPython` to run Python "
"code. However, when your Python code grow bigger, putting hundreds of lines "
"inside `runPython` is not scalable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:8
msgid "For larger projects, the best way to run Python code with Pyodide is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:10
msgid "create a Python package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:11
msgid ""
"load your Python package into the Pyodide (Emscripten) virtual file system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:12
msgid "import the package with `let mypkg = pyodide.pyimport(\"mypkgname\")`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:13
msgid "call into your package with `mypkg.some_api(some_args)`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:15
msgid "Using wheels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:17
msgid ""
"The best way of serving custom Python code is making it a package in the "
"wheel (.whl) format. If the package is built as a `wheel` file, you can use "
"{py:func}`micropip.install` to install the package. See {ref}"
"`loading_packages` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:21
msgid "Packages with C extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:24
msgid ""
"If your Python code contains C extensions, it needs to be built for Pyodide "
"first (See the [pyodide-build documentation](https://pyodide-build."
"readthedocs.io/en/latest/))."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:28
msgid "Loading then importing Python code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:30
msgid ""
"It is also possible to download and import Python code from an external "
"source. We recommend that you serve all files in an archive, instead of "
"individually downloading each Python script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:33
msgid "From Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:35
msgid ""
"// Downloading an archive\n"
"await pyodide.runPythonAsync(`\n"
"    from pyodide.http import pyfetch\n"
"    response = await pyfetch(\"https://.../your_package.tar.gz\") # .zip, ."
"whl, ...\n"
"    await response.unpack_archive() # by default, unpacks to the current "
"dir\n"
"`)\n"
"pkg = pyodide.pyimport(\"your_package\");\n"
"pkg.do_something();\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:46
msgid ""
"// Downloading a single file\n"
"await pyodide.runPythonAsync(`\n"
"    from pyodide.http import pyfetch\n"
"    response = await pyfetch(\"https://.../script.py\")\n"
"    with open(\"script.py\", \"wb\") as f:\n"
"        f.write(await response.bytes())\n"
"`)\n"
"pkg = pyodide.pyimport(\"script\");\n"
"pkg.do_something();\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:58
msgid "What is pyfetch?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:61
msgid ""
"Pyodide provides {py:func}`~pyodide.http.pyfetch`, which is a convenient "
"wrapper of JavaScript `fetch`. See {ref}`load-external-files-in-pyodide` for "
"more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:66
msgid "From JavaScript"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:68
msgid ""
"let response = await fetch(\"https://.../your_package.tar.gz\"); // .zip, ."
"whl, ...\n"
"let buffer = await response.arrayBuffer();\n"
"await pyodide.unpackArchive(buffer, \"gztar\"); // by default, unpacks to "
"the current dir\n"
"pyodide.pyimport(\"your_package\");\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:75
msgid "Warning on unpacking a wheel package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:78
msgid ""
"Since a wheel package is actually a zip archive, you can use {js:func}"
"`pyodide.unpackArchive` to unpack a wheel package, instead of using {py:func}"
"`micropip.install`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:82
msgid ""
"However, {mod}`micropip` does dependency resolution when installing "
"packages, while {js:func}`pyodide.unpackArchive` simply unpacks the archive. "
"So you must be aware of that each dependencies of a package need to be "
"installed manually before unpacking a wheel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:87
msgid ""
"_Future plans:_ we are planning to support a method for a static dependency "
"resolution (See: [pyodide#2045](https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide/"
"issues/2045))."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:91
msgid "Running external code directly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:93
msgid ""
"If you want to run a single Python script from an external source in a "
"simplest way, you can:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/loading-custom-python-code.md:96
msgid ""
"pyodide.runPython(await (await fetch(\"https://some_url/.../code.py\"))."
"text());\n"
msgstr ""
